args: (I'm pretty sure that's Odetta.\nShe's always by herself.)
(I can't just leave her alone.\nMy sister senses are tingling...!)
(She might not welcome my attention,\nbut it should be fine if I just say hi, right?)
Not really; I was just hoping we could\ntalk a bit.
Ah, I see. I looked sad, didn't I?
W-well, maybe a little. I thought you\nmight like some company.
You needn't worry. I know solitude well,\nand I actually quite enjoy it. I often\njourney on my own, you see.
She might like being alone, but if she\nkeeps pushing people away like that\nshe'll ALWAYS be alone.
Ugh, now I'm really worried. Maybe I'm\nbeing a teensy bit nosy, but...oh well!
There you are, Odetta! Are you hungry?\nI tried making your favorite.
You've been near me at my every waking\nmoment—but did I ask for such attention?\nNO!
Louise, I appreciate your concern.\nBut as I said before, I LIKE being alone.
Odetta... I'm sorry. I get overprotective\nsometimes. It's a bad habit.
I got the message though; I won't try\nto talk to you again. ...Bye.
Good, Odetta, you got just as you wanted.\nYou are strong, and solitude is your\nmost trusted companion.
(Have I been relying on Louise's\nlullabies lately?)
...Morning already? But the sun is\nso high in the sky... Did I oversleep?!
But it was my turn to take the watch!\nWhy didn't Louise wake me u—oh...
(She's been waking me up lately...\nDid I grow accustomed to it?)
Is something amiss, Odetta? \nThat was a mighty sigh.
I see. So, you can no longer live\nwithout Louise.
Uh, I didn't go THAT far.
Perhaps you should swallow your pride\nand apologize.
I'm not sure it would matter.\nI wasn't exactly kind in my dismissal.
Odetta, you are accustomed to thinking\nonly of yourself, yes? This is not a slight;\nmerely an observation.
Louise is the opposite. She puts all others\nbefore herself—a trait she developed\nthrough caring for her younger brother.
For you, I would think Louise's perspective\nto be an entirely new world.
She is kind, and understanding.\nDo not be afraid; just speak with her.
I came to apologize. I should never\nhave spoken to you so harshly.
I'm not accustomed to being cared for\nwithout expectation of reward, and I\ntook my confusion out on you.
Aww. You're a good girl, aren't you Odetta?\nThank you for coming to apologize.
Oh, excuse me. Patting people on\nthe head is something of a habit of mine.
Not at all. I admit, I was a bit overbearing.
Wow. We really are COMPLETELY different\npeople.
But that's why I'd like to know more about\nyou—and I won't run away this time.
Do you think we could be friends, Louise?
What are you talking about, Odetta?
O-oh! Well, um, thank you.\nYou truly are a marvel of kindness.
You seem in good spirits, Louise.\nDid you make up with Odetta?
How'd you know about all that?
Hm, I see. What did she say?
That she was confused by your mothering.\nI am glad to know you made amends—\nbut may I say something?
I understand you were met with\nsome resistance from Odetta,\ndespite your best intentions.
But I also know you are much too\nstubborn to give up in the face of\nsuch opposition.

You only did so because you believed
it the most effective strategy—as if
dealing with a rebellious child.
Am I correct?
But that's okay, right? We ended up\nfriends, and now I can take care of\nher—
No. I already had some understanding\nof what sort of person you are.
Your plan worked; you got me to leave\nmy solitude of my own volition.
You are SO CUTE when you're honest!\nLet your big sis give you a big squishy\nhug!
Come on, remember what happened the\nlast time you kicked up a fuss?
I'll raise you up good and strong.\nJust leave everything to me!
I am already a grown woman,\nthank you very much!
They do seem a perfect pair...
All right—ALL RIGHT! Let go already!\nYou can hug me, just not so tight.
I know I can be a bit much, but can we\nstill be friends?
Considering the silly ordeal we just\nendured, and that we only came out\ncloser to each other...
